157. Brix' proposed change of the order of the MSS. to Quid credis? postquam &c.‚ Quoi optigerat, fuqitant, &a is unnecessary, though we have similar transpositions in the MSS. at Mil. 593, Pers. 691. It is also wrong to translate quoi as ‘cuicumque’ and understand the sentence as omnes quoi optiqerat fugitant &c Quoi must refer to Philopolemus. opti- gerat, current in this sense, eg. Cic. Vat. 5. 12 eum tibi maquo elamore aquaria provincia sorte optiqisset.

159. Multigeneribus. In Stich. 383 we have another form of expres- sion: Poste uuqueuta multiqeuerum multa (cf. omnimodis, multimodis for omuibus modis, multis modis). Lucr. ii. 335 uses Abl. Plur. multiqeuis (cf. Virgil's omnigenum Gen. Pl.):

Percipe, multigenis quam sint variata figuris.

160. Primumdum, a formation of the type of etiamdum, interdum, &c.‚ not unfrequent in Plautus, eg. Most. 400 Omnium primumdum haee aedes iam face occlusae sieut, Truc. 31 Primumdum merces annua: is primus bolust‚ Trin. 98 primumdum omnium, ‘first of all! Pistorensibus, a pun on (1) pistor, ‘miller,’ later ‘baker,' (2) the town of Pistoria in Etruria. On the change of meaning of the word pistor cf. Pliny N. H. XVIII. xi. 28 Pistores (i.e. bakers) Itomae uon fuere ad Persicum usque bellum anuis ab urbe condita super DLXXX. Ipsi partem faciebant Quirites ...certumque fit Atei Capitonis sententia cocos tum pauent lautioribus coquere solitos pistoresque tautum eos qui far pz'sebaut nominatos. This statement of Pliny argues for the post-Plautine authorship of v. 161.
